Breakfast cereal: Choosing a price

  • To decide on what price to charge, a firm needs information about demand of a product
  • consider the demand curve for Apple-Cinnamon Cheerios, introduced by General Mills in 1989 (in the next slide)

Figure 1. Shows demand curve

  • shows the relationship between price and quantity demanded
    • For example, if price is $3 customers will demand 25,000 pounds
  • If you had to choose a price for a bag of cereal, how would you do it?
  • Objective is to maximize profit
  • \(Total cost = unit\; cost \times quantity\)
    • = \(2\times Q\)
  • \(Total Revenue = price \times quantity\)
    • = \(P \times Q\)

  • \(profit = total \; revenue - total\; cost\)

  • Now, the formula for profit: \(profit = (P-2) \times Q\)

Isoprofit curves as the firm’s indifference curve

  • Once you have the profit function (from the previous slide), given the exact value of profit, you can find combinations of \(P\) and \(Q\) to give you that value of profit.
  • For any value of profit, you can then plot the combinations of price and quantity as given in the figure below.

    Figure 2. Isoprofit curve for Cheerios

Demand and Isoprofit curve

  • if you look at the profit function \(profit = (P-2) \times Q\), you should note that profit can be increased by increasing both \(P\) and \(Q\)
  • however, it is not possible to increase both \(P\) and \(Q\) simultaneously, as \(P\) increases \(Q\) is likely to fall
    • if price of something increases you are going to buy less of it
  • Hence, the profit function (indifference curve of the firm) is constrained by the demand curve

    Figure 3. Isoprofit curves and Demand Curve

  • In Figure 3, demand curve acts as a constraint whereas isoprofit curve is the firm’s indifference curve. As a mangager, you pick price such that it maximizes your profit. Here, choosing point E, where the demand curve is tangential to the isoprofit curve, allows you to maximize profit.

  • In point E, price \(P=\$4.4\) and \(Q=14,000 \;pounds\).

  • The isoprofit curve is your indifference curve, and its slope at any point represents the trade-off you are willing to make between P and Q. Note that the slope of the indifference curve is also the marginal rate of substitution (MRS). The trade-off that a person is willing to make between two goods.

  • The slope of the demand curve is the trade-off you are constrained to make—your MRT, or the rate at which the demand curve allows you to ‘transform’ quantity into price. You cannot raise the price without lowering the quantity, because fewer consumers will be buy a more expensive product.

Economies of Scale

  • What are some internal structures that can explain why firms like Walmart, Amazon have grown so big.

  • Technological Advancement - Use fewer inputs per unit of production.
  • Cost Advantages - Large firms have more bargaining power, so they can get inputs for cheaper. In a case of a large firm, fixed costs such as advertisement will contribute less to the cost per unit \(average\;fixed\;cost=\frac{Total\;Fixed\;Cost}{Q}\).
    • Note that as \(Q\) increases; the average fixed cost decreases.

  • When expanding firms can encounter economies of scale. This means that as inputs double, output increases by more than double.

Questions Which of the following statements is correct?

  • If a firm’s technology exhibits constant returns to scale, doubling the inputs leads to doubling of the output level.
    • If a firm’s technology exhibits decreasing returns to scale, doubling the inputs more than doubles the output level.
    • If a firm’s technology exhibits economies of scale, costs per unit will fall as the firm expands its production.
    • If a firm’s technology exhibits diseconomies of scale, doubling the inputs leads to less than doubling of the output level.

Production: The cost function for beautiful cars

  • Consider that you own a factory that produces cars. As a factory you will be incuring cost of various kinds.
    • labor, machines, steel, rent
  • More cars you produce higher your cost.

Figure 4. Cost Structure of Cars

  • In Figure 4 (top), cost of production increases as you produce more cars.
  • In the bottom of Figure 4, average cost \(Average\;cost=\frac{Total\;cost}{Q}\) first decreases and then starts to increase
    • decrease in average cost at first can be because of economies of scale, after a certain point, average cost will begin to increase as resources will have been exhausted.

Figure 5. Total cost, average and marginal cost

  • Figure 5 shows the marginal cost. At each point on the cost function, the marginal cost (MC) is the additional cost of producing one more unit of output, which corresponds to the slope of the cost function. If cost increases by ∆C when quantity is increased by ∆Q, the marginal cost can be estimated by: \(MC=\frac{\Delta C}{\Delta Q}\).
    • In other words MC is the slope of the Total cost, can one can calculate MC at each quantity of cars \((Q\), by calculating the slope at each point.
    • As the slope of total cost is upward sloping and gets steeper as more cars are produced, marginal cost will increase with \(Q\).
  • What is the relationship between AC and MC?
    • It can be seen from Figure 7 (bottom) that as MC increases, AC first falls. But at the segment when AC is falling MC is always below AC. Eventually, as MC keeps rising it will drag the AC upwards.
    • MC intersects AC at the lowest point of AC.

Demand and Isoprofit

Figure 6. Demand Curve

  • The demand curve depends on consumer’s willingness to pay. As P increases lower portion of people will be willing to pay for the car (since price is higher), as P decreases more people will be ready to buy the car. This inverse relationship between price and quantity demanded (cars) is known as the law of demand.

Figure 7. Marginal Cost and Isoprofit

  • Profit: is the difference between firm’s total revenue \(TR\) and total cost \(C(Q)\). \[\begin{align*} \text{profit} &= \text{total revenue} - \text{total costs} \\ &= PQ - C(Q) \end{align*}\]

  • it can be written as, \(profit = Q(P-\frac{C(Q)}{Q})\), where \(\frac{C(Q)}{Q}=AC\).
    • note that the shape of the isoprofit curve will depend on the AC.

Setting Price and Quantity to Maximize Profit

Figure 8. Price to Maximize Profit

  • In Figure 8, the profit maximization price at point E. Here, the demand curve is tangential to the darker blue isoprofit curve.
    • P* = $5,440 and Q* = 32
  • Also, note that the demand curve is also the feasible frontier. The slope of the demand curve is the marginal rate of transformation (MRT) of lower price into greater quantity sold.

  • The isoprofit curve is the indifference curve, and its slope is the marginal rate of substitution (MRS) in profit creation, between selling more and charging more.

  • At profit maximization, \(MRT=MRS\).

Profit maximization using marginal revenue and marginal cost

  • In last few sildes, we looked at finding profit maximization price and quantity using the tangential point between the demand curve and the isoprofit line.
  • We not look at maximization of profit using marginal revenue (MR) and (MC).
  • \(Revenue (R)=P\timesQ\), and marginal revenue is the increase in revenue because of increasing quantity from \(Q\) to \(Q+1\).
  • The figure below shows calculation of MR when \(Q=20\)

Setting Price and Quantity to Maximize Profit

Figure 9. Marginal Revenue

Q P R
Q=20 P=$6,400 R=$128,000
Q=21 P=$6,320 R=$132,720
\(\Delta\)Q=1 \(\Delta\) P=80 \(\Delta\) MR=$4,720
  • Note that \(MR=\frac{\Delta R}{\Delta Q}\) as calculated above. MR can also be found by looking at the net of gain and loss. When price moves to $6,320, the revenue from one additional car is $6,320, but there is a loss in the revenue encountered from lowering the price to $6,320 for last 20 cars by $80.
    • Net change in revenue is $6,320 - \(80\)$20=\(4,720\), which is also same as the marginal revenue as calculated above.

Finding profit maximization price and quantity using MC=MR

Figure 10. Profit Maximizing Price and Quantity

  • In Figure 10, the top figure shows the demand curve. The middle one shows the marginal cost and marginal revenue (Calculated using the demand curve) plotted together. The bottom one shows the profit as a function of quantity.
  • it can be seen that profit is the highest when \(MC=MR\). This is because if \(MR>MC\), the firm will increase profit by producing more, and if \(MR<MC\) the firm will increase profit by reducing production. The ideal point is where \(MC=MR\).
